Load the data

In [2]:
# first let's load the same data and preprocess it exactly the same way we did before
# load the data
raw_data = yfinance.download(tickers = '^GSPC ^FTSE ^N225 ^GDAXI', start = '1994-01-07', end = '2018-01-29',
                            interval = '1d', group_by = 'ticker', auto_adjust = True, treads = True)

# create a copy of the data
df_comp = raw_data.copy()

# rename the columns
df_comp['spx'] = df_comp['^GSPC'].Close[:]
df_comp['dax'] = df_comp['^GDAXI'].Close[:]
df_comp['ftse'] = df_comp['^FTSE'].Close[:]
df_comp['nikkei'] = df_comp['^N225'].Close[:]

# remove the first row
df_comp = df_comp.iloc[1:]

# remove the original columns
del df_comp['^GSPC']
del df_comp['^GDAXI']
del df_comp['^FTSE']
del df_comp['^N225']

# using b tells Python to expect missing values when the date falls on a Saturday or a Sunday.
# let's apply the asfreq() method and use the value "b" instead
# using the value "b" avoids adding many unnecessary time periods
df_comp = df_comp.asfreq('b')

# fill the missing values
df_comp = df_comp.fillna(method = 'ffill')

# creating returns
df_comp['ret_spx'] = df_comp.spx.pct_change(1) * 100
df_comp['ret_ftse'] = df_comp.spx.pct_change(1) * 100
df_comp['ret_dax'] = df_comp.spx.pct_change(1) * 100
df_comp['ret_nikkei'] = df_comp.spx.pct_change(1) * 100

# splitting the data
size = int(len(df_comp) * 0.8)
df_train, df_test = df_comp.iloc[:size], df_comp[size:]

In [4]:
# the last date is "2013-04-05" so the start date will be "2013-04-06"
# the start and end dates must be business days, otherwise the code will result in an error
start_date = '2013-04-06'
end_date = '2018-01-01'

# let's load the AR(1) model with the pickle module
model_ar = pickle.load(open('/Users/papa/Documents/model_ar.sav', 'rb'))

# make the prediction
df_pred = model_ar.predict(start = start_date, end = end_date)

# plot the prediction
df_pred[start_date:end_date].plot(figsize = (20,5), color = 'red')
plt.title('Predictions', size = 24)
plt.show()
In [5]:
# the plot show a curve which is an unrealistic one
# this is because the AR model is so bad at estimating non-stationary data
# now let's compare this plot to the real test data
df_pred[start_date:end_date].plot(figsize = (20,5), color = 'red')
df_test.ftse[start_date:end_date].plot(color = 'blue')
plt.title('Predictions vs actual', size = 24)
plt.show()
In [6]:
# the plot clearly shows that the AR model is not a good estimator of non-stationary data

Forecasting returns with AR and MA models

In [7]:
# we will now switch to returns since they are stationary
end_date = '2018-01-01'

# fit the AR model
model_ret_ar = ARIMA(df_train.ret_ftse[1:], order = (1,0,0))
results_ret_ar = model_ret_ar.fit()

# make the predictions
df_pred_ar = results_ret_ar.predict(start = start_date, end = end_date)

# plot the predictions
df_pred_ar[start_date:end_date].plot(figsize = (20,5), color = 'red')
df_test.ret_ftse[start_date:end_date].plot(color = 'blue')
plt.title('Predictions vs Actual (Returns)', size = 24)
plt.show()
In [8]:
# the prediction line is centered around zero
# this means that this model makes no predictions since it assumes all future returns will be 0, or extremely close to it
# this indicates that the coeffcients of the past values as well as the values themselves have low absolute values

# check out the summary table of this model
results_ret_ar.summary()

Auto ARIMA forecasting

In [18]:
# let's load the saved auto ARIMA model
#model_auto = pickle.load(open('/Users/papa/Documents/auto_arima.sav', 'rb'))

model_auto = auto_arima(df_train.ret_ftse[1:], exogenous = df_train[['ret_spx', 'ret_dax', 'ret_nikkei']][1:],
                       m = 5, max_p = 5, max_q = 5, max_P = 5, max_Q = 5)

# now it is time to make the predictions
# note that the predict method of the auto_arima model doesn't return a dataframe but a numpy array
# so we need to use the df.DataFrame method to convert the predictions into a dataframe format
df_pred_auto = pd.DataFrame(model_auto.predict(n_periods = len(df_test[start_date:end_date]),
                                              exogenous = df_test[['ret_spx', 'ret_dax', 'ret_nikkei']][start_date:end_date]),
                           index = df_test[start_date:end_date].index)

# plot the predictions
df_pred_auto.plot(figsize = (20,5), color = 'red')
df_test.ret_ftse[start_date:end_date].plot(color = 'blue')
plt.title('Auto Model Predictions vs Real Data', size = 24)
plt.show()

In [20]:
# the predictions match the testing set very accurately
# as long as we provide the auto_arima method with enough information, it's bound to give us a reasonable solution
# all the models that perform well rely on exogenous variables
# however, exogenous variables are hardly ever available when we wanna make long term predictions
# our MAX models rely on outside data much more than they do on past values (AR) or past errors (MA)
